Management Revolution or the End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as previously it was about imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to market-conquering strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially of R&D and, even more so, of business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) “requires that all parties involved ... have proactive behavior and a forward-looking vision”; it needs from employees a commitment that completely opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory that the American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent research of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanistic management position, unsuited to the world today.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilization Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into all business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make it part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, business executives can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “in place.”
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
