When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can surrender unhindered to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, those who experience sleep-like states during wakefulness, or see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are most often regarded in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as manic.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
The fault lies with our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes blur the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality.
Dream-modified alert states of consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Casta<0xC3><0xB1>eda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain — especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin, and acetylcholine — has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disrupted.
During a schizophrenic psychosis very often appear complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts.
Gravity no longer has power over it.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of waking sleep, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the misplaced, squalid forms".
It’s the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red noses like blood, deformed, grinding teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Shouting and malignant voices resound from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls two wires from the stereo, ties them to form a hanging knot, and secures them to a hook on the ceiling.
It rises in a horn and puts the knot around the neck.
Jump.
The rope is loose.
What a lesson for you!, shout the voices in a chorus that breaks the eardrums, "Go to the clinic and have them cure you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first one almost 20 years ago.
The cause of this was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, in addition he is manic-depressive, taking medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and they fall into a state of overexcitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the gates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed to it.
At the same time he enters a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still an unknown why our brain makes convertibles.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to temporarily lose touch with reality.
But not all people develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes, there are other determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains an unknown how this alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Also the influence of the environment plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a prior disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmitting system.
When the brain heats up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten, of L<0xC3><0xBC>beck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreale Welt in nous Kopf (The unreal world in our head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and craniofacial trauma.
surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also suffers from hallucinations.
According to Kasten, hallucinations are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or poorly cohibted; when our brain gets hot, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, the evil of loves or other brain states of exception.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported experiencing hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it wasn't for those pictures and the voices.
Sometimes, during recess, it happens that a clumsy boy with long, dark hair speaks to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her in surprise; no one but her hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a little strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she’s not dreaming.
She is awake and sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting in the next bench.
You can even feel their presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the guy.
Sometimes she wonders if she's crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he’s in class he can sometimes not follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is introducing a new partner, while for the rest he explains the mathematical equations visibly and audibly.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for the dream to arrive, which often comes late and is scarce, he does not know how to distinguish whether she is awake or dreaming, if the images she sees, the lashes or the girl with bloody cuts in her arms and legs, appear in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, yell at the figures.
Her parents and friends haven't told her anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed last year on selectivity and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, hallucinations disappeared.
Ever since she got in touch over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, she knows she's not crazy.
Insanity is also a work of art out of desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while he will begin to have hallucinations.
I think that the brain is unoccupied and it is in charge of seeking entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, had little fear of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he has been calling dad since he has used reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. “Every experience,” says Kasten, “takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies night fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate his hallucinations as a special skill.
Boundary situation between sleep and hallucination
in this overly conscious world, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful illness but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person experiencing them considers real and that subsequently cannot differentiate from being awake.
The dream-conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with a trauma or a disease, such as in patients with polyrradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while being fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische L<0xC3><0xA4>hmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of self or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a self-imaginary world that is decoupled from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change of world, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an insurmountable situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the void of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as an action of soul-saving.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several-day trips after heart valve surgery with heart transplant included, while his body was condemned to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by himself and visited strange places of other times: he was lying in bed, an elderly man on board a sanatorium on a train, a robot was watching over his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek man on a motorcycle hijacked him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the snow-covered Alps and found himself with a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in the irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intense even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our everyday experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneiricism, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Each modification of the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
