75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and career of women in Spain', developed by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, start living together as a couple, advance first motherhood, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have less offspring.
“Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life path to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on motherhood, although less on the timing of mating," explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
The level of studies is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and when they have the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the older the age at which they marry and the age at which they have their first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years old, those with elementary and higher studies have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
"Another division among women is also established based on their level of studies.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, middle- or upper-level ones reverse this sequence and prioritize getting a stable job as a pre-marital condition and the arrival of a child,” Delgado says.
