Emergency brake assistance is now mandatory.
As with ABS anti-lock braking and will happen with ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, this is already the case in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of shortage is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, because of its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency brake assistant does what it does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the piston that gives the driver.
But it doesn’t always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by car parts manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car in stopping.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In the event that it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
