Distribution
This apparent paradox is explained by UEFA’s complicated money-sharing procedure.
For this exercise, the body chaired by Michel Platini plans to receive 1.090 million euros for the Champions League.
From this money UEFA will dedicate 413.1 million for the fixed payments: each of the 20 clubs that participated in the previous qualifying round (among them Atlético de Madrid) received 2.1 million.
In addition, those who managed to participate received 3.8 million just for being there, in addition to another 550,000 euros for each party they compete.
There are also bonuses to win (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>800,000) and tie (400,000 for each team). The eighth-finalists will receive three million each; the eight fourth-finalists, 3.3 million.
The last four will be pocketed 4 million each.
The champion will win 9 million, compared to 5.2 million of the finalist.
Thus, in terms of fixed payments, a club will enter at least 7.1 million, and a maximum of 31.2 million.
Bar<0xC3><0xA7>a, on the other hand, pocketed $2.5 million for winning the European Super Cup in August.
But there are also variable payments, to which 337.8 million are allocated.
This money is distributed according to the proportional value of each television market.
The Spanish language is one of the main ones, and it has four allocated places.
The previous year’s champion is left with 40% of the money allocated, 30% for the second, 20% for the third and 10% for the fourth.
The other part will be paid according to the number of matches played in this year’s edition.
